%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Introduction} 
\label{sec:Introduction}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Neoclassical economic growth theory attributes output ($Y$) to factors of production: capital stock ($K$) and labor ($L$). The Cobb-Douglas production function is the canonical representation of indexed economic output ($y$) as a function of indexed labor ($l$), indexed capital stock ($k$), and an exogenous, time-dependent technological progress term ($A$):

\begin{equation} \label{eq:CD}
  y = A k^\alpha l^\beta; A = \mathrm{e}^{\lambda(t-t_0)}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $y \equiv Y/Y_\mathrm{0}$, $k \equiv K/K_\mathrm{0}$, and $l \equiv L/L_\mathrm{0}$; with $Y$ represented by GDP, $K$ expressed in currency units, $L$ expressed in workers/year or work-hours/year, time ($t$) measured in years, e being the base of the natural logarithm, and subscripts ``0'' indicating values at an initial year. $A$ is a unitless technological progress term, with $\lambda$ indicating the pace of technological progress (in units of year$^{-1}$).\footnote{Dimensionless, indexed quantities are represented by lower-case symbols ($y$, $k$, $l$, $e$, $q$, $x$, and $u$), and dimensional quantities are represented by upper-case symbols ($Y$, $K$, $L$, $E$, $Q$, $X$, and $U$). One exception is the technolgical progress term $A$, which is dimensionless but written in upper-case by convention.} Neoclassical economic growth theory makes no attempt to understand the mechanisms by which technological progress ($A$) affects economic growth, nor does it attempt to describe how technological progress ($A$) might vary from one economy to the next. Mathematically, $A$ is a fitting parameter that aligns the predictions of Equation \ref{eq:CD} with historical data. Typically, the constraint $\alpha + \beta = 1$ is assumed, indicating constant returns to scale.

As shown in Equation \ref{eq:CD} above, neoclassical economic theory does not include an explicit term for the role of energy in economic growth. However, \citet{Bashmakov:2007ek} and \citet{Murphy:2011jh} indicate that the importance of energy may far outweigh its cost share in the economy. That neoclassical economic growth theory ignores energy is, therefore, cause for concern, and inquiry into the proper approach for including energy as a factor of production in economic growth modeling is both relevant and important.

Some energy economists augment economic growth models with energy being an additional (or the only) factor of production. However, there is little agreement on how this should be done. Neither the mathematical form of the energy-augmented production function nor the quantification of energy are consistent in the literature. Furthermore, there has been little empirical work done to assess the predictive ability of various energy-augmented production functions for different types of economies. In addition, very few studies of the importance of energy in economic growth include rigorous statistical assessments of energy-related fitting parameters. This paper attempts to contribute to the literature by applying statistically rigorous methods along three coordinates of analysis: form of the energy augmented production function, energy quantification, and type of economy.

