%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

This section describes the three coordinates of analysis and briefly reviews literature related to each.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Mathematical Forms of the Energy-augmented Production Function} \label{sec:Prod_Func_Forms}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In this paper, we assess three prominent energy-augmented production functions appear in the literature: Cobb-Douglas (CDe), Constant Elasticity of Substitution (CESe), and LINear EXponential (LINEX). The following sections describe each.

%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Energy-augmented Cobb-Douglas Production Function (CDe)} 
\label{sec:CDe}
%------------------------------

Similar to Equation \ref{eq:CD}, the energy-augmented Cobb-Douglas production function is

\begin{equation} \label{eq:CDe}
  y = A k^\alpha l^\beta e^\gamma; A = \mathrm{e}^{\lambda(t-t_0)}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $e \equiv E/E_0$, and $E$ is in units of energy per time. The energy-augmented Cobb-Douglas production function is often assumed to have constant returns to scale for the three factors of production: $\alpha + \beta + \gamma = 1$.

\citet{Ayres:2008cl} uses Equation \ref{eq:CDe} with exergy ($x$) and useful work ($u$) quantifications for $e$ to describe historic Japanese and American economies from 1900-2000. \citet{Froling:2009vo} uses an energy-augmented Cobb-Douglas production function with thermal energy quantification ($q$) to describe output for the global economy from 1800-1970. Fr\"{o}ling's model endogenizes labor with respect to fertility and mortality rates and separates thermal energy into two types: biomass energy and coal energy. \citet{Serrenho:2010vq} use the log transform of the energy-augmented Cobb-Douglas function with thermal energy quantification ($q$) to describe output for the EU-15 countries. Serrenho divides thermal energy into renewables, non-renewables, wastes, and imports.

