\subsection{Quantification of Energy} 
\label{sec:Quantification_of_Energy}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The literature shows three quantifications of energy ($E$) used in energy-augmented production functions: thermal energy ($Q$), exergy ($X$), and useful work ($U$). Thermal energy ($Q$) is the heat content of an energy carrier. Exergy ($X$) is the maximum useful work that can be extracted from an energy carrier by a process that brings the system into equilibrium with a heat reservoir (typically the surrounding environment). Useful work ($U$) includes the direct energy that goes into an economy, including work from machines, human muscles, and animals. Firms pay for thermal energy ($Q$), but useful work ($U$) alters the size and shape of materials, keeps lights on, and transports goods to consumers. Not all forms of energy are created equal in terms of ability to generate economic activity \citep{Cleveland:2000vl, Warr:2010ht}. Exergy ($X$), and to a greater extent, useful work ($U$) account for the useful energy that goes into generating economic activity, thereby reflecting the ``quality'' of each energy type and the efficiency of machines and devices typically used to convert thermal energy ($Q$) into useful work ($U$).

Most energy economists use thermal energy ($q$) for the energy factor of production ($e$) in energy-augmented production functions, including \citet{Stern:2012ey}, \citet{Froling:2009vo}, \citet{Serrenho:2010vq}, and \citet{Kummel:1980wx,Kummel:1982vy,Kummel:1985vz,Kummel:1989tf,Kummel:2002tx,Kummel:2010vz}. \citet{Warr:2010ga} introduced the idea of using exergy ($x$) and useful work ($u$) in energy-augmentd production functions to account for efficiency gains in energy production and consumption over the last century. 

We know of no statistically-rigorous comparisons of the predictive ability of each energy quantification in the various types of production functions discussed in Section \ref{sec:Prod_Func_Forms}. We analyze all three quantifications of energy ($Q$, $X$, and $U$) for developed economies and thermal energy ($Q$) and exergy ($X$) for all other economies.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Economy Types} 
\label{sec:Economy_Types}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In the energy-economic growth literature, the focus is almost exclusively on developed economies from North America or Europe. Examples include \citet{Kummel:1980wx} applying LINEX to describe the West German economy, \citet{Serrenho:2010vq} applying Cobb-Douglas variants to EU-15 countries, \citet{VanderWerf:2008tc} applying CES nesting variants to the 12 OECD countries, \citet{Lecca:2011kr} applying CES nesting variants to the Scottish economy, \citet{Stern:2012ey} applying CES to describe the Swedish economy, and \citet{Warr:2012cg} using LINEX and Cobb-Douglas to describe the Austrian, American, British, and Japanese economies.

But, the nearly-complete focus on developed economies misses the role that energy plays in the development process. In this paper we analyze at least two economies in each of the following four categories: Developed (technologically advanced with high standards of living), BRICS\footnote{Brazil, Russia, India, China, and South Africa} (rapid economic growth with standards of living below that of developed economies), Petrol (petroleum is a substantial source of GDP); and LDCs\footnote{Lesser Developed Countries} (living standards near subsistence levels). (See Table \ref{tab:Economy_Examples}.)

