\section{Sources of Data}
\label{sec:Sources_of_Data}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

To assess energy-augmented models of economic growth along the coordinates of analysis outlined in Section \ref{sec:Coordinates}, historical data for economic output ($Y$), capital stock ($K$), labor ($L$), thermal energy ($Q$), exergy ($X$), and useful work ($U$) are required. Subsections below describe sources for and calculations to obtain historical data. A final subsection presents the historical data in graphical form.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Economic Output} 
\label{sec:Economic_Output_Data}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

We measure economic output ($Y$) by real gross domestic product (GDP). GDP data in real 2005 U.S. dollars for developed countries (1980--2011) and all other countries (1991--2011) was obtained from the World Bank's Global Economic Prospects (GEP) database \citep{WorldBankGEP:2013a}.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Capital Stock} 
\label{sec:Capital_Stock_Data}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Gross capital stock in real 2005 U.S. dollars for developed countries (1980--2011) and all other countries (1991--2011) was obtained from the World Bank's Global Economic Prospects (GEP) database \citep{WorldBankGEP:2013a}.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Labor and Employment}
\label{sec:Labor_Data}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Total employment and average hours worked per worker per year for the developed nations (United States, United Kingdom, and Japan) for 1980--2011 were obtained from the United States \citet{BLS:2011a}. Total hours worked per year was calculated by multiplying total employment by average hours worked per worker per year.  

The World Bank's World Development Indicators database \citep{WorldBankWDI:2013a} provides the employment to population ratio for people fifteen and older, total population, and a percentage of people under fifteen for other nations (South Africa, China, Iran, Saudi Arabia, Tanzania, and Zambia) for 1991--2011. The population of people under fifteen was subtracted from total population to calculate the population of people fifteen and older. Total employment was calculated by multiplying the employment to population ratio of people fifteen and older by the population of people fifteen and older.

